ermanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir. Henry de Vernon was born about 1230, in Shipbrook, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Mary Dacre. He married Ann Shrewberry in 1245, in Davenham, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1230–":"umbes 1230–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","1224–Female":"1224–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","Abt 1230":"umbes 1230","1205":"1205","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1245":"1245","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","Davenham, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Davenham, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shipbrook, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shipbrook, Davenham, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1230–":"noin 1230–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1235–Female":"1235–Kuollut","1224–Female":"1224–Kuollut","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","Abt 1230":"noin 1230","1205":"1205","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1245":"1245","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","Davenham, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Davenham, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shipbrook, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shipbrook, Davenham, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1230–":"environ 1230–Décédé","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","1235–Female":"1235–Décédée","1224–Female":"1224–Décédée","1250–Female":"1250–Décédée","1205–Female":"1205–Décédée","Abt 1230":"environ 1230","1205":"1205","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1245":"1245","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","Davenham, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Davenham, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Shipbrook, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Shipbrook, Davenham, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Sir. Henry de Vernon est né environ 1230, à Shipbrook, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Mary Dacre. Il a épousé Ann